Fifth Ave., at, adjoining and north of the N.E. corner of East 78th Street, showing prominently the James B. Duke (Doris Duke, 1936) home, that bears No. 1 East 78th Street. Adjacent to same is the 5-story Payne Whitney home, No. 972 Fifth Ave. On the extreme left is the Edith M. Feder (1936) home, No. 973. This latter is adjacent to the A. Van-Stuyvesant Jr. home (S.E. corner of 79th Street), which is not shown.
[About 1910.] No construction not completed until 1911.

969 and 968-5 Fifth Ave., (right) at and adjoining the S.E. corner of East 78th Street. The corner building was demolished in 1925 and left the adjoining property, No. 968-5, the Jacob H. Schiff standing. These two parcels will be improved with an 18-story apartment house according to the New York Sun, September 29, 1937. Shown on the extreme left is No. 2 East 78th Street, a four-story building adjoining the corner.

About 1920.

78th Street, at and adjoining the S.E. corner of Fifth Avenue.
About 1922.

Irving Underhill.
Gift of E. M. Jenks.

968-5, 964, 963 and 960 Fifth Ave., east side, south from East 78th to 77th Streets, showing prominently the Jacob H. Schiff house, No. 968-5, adjoining the S.E. corner (empty lot, former No. 969). On the extreme right is a part of No. 960, the Clark mansion, located at the N.E. corner of 77th Street. This, and its neighbor No. 963 were demolished in 1926 and on their site erected a large apartment house. The Schiff house, together with the empty lot will form the site of an 18-story apartment building according to the N.Y. Sun September 29, 1937.

June 1925.

Fifth Ave., east side, north from East 78th Street, showing prominently the James B. Duke (Doris Duke, 1936) house, No. 1 East 78th Street. Adjacent to same is the 5-story Payne Whitney home, No. 972 Fifth Ave. The two other structures occupying this front between 78th and 79th Streets are, No. 973 (Edith M. Feder, 1936) and No. 974 (A. Van Stuyvesant Jr., 1956); the latter being at the S.E. corner of 79th Street.

June 1925.

Fifth Ave., east side, south from (No. 972), a point midway between East 79th to 78th Streets and across the latter. Shown are the Payne Whitney house (No. 972 Fifth Ave.) and the Doris Duke house (No. 1 East 78th Street).

July 21, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

East 78th Street, south side, east from Fifth and across Madison Aves.

July 21, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

4 East 78th Street, south side, east of Fifth Avenue (right). Adjacent to the brownstone enumerated is a clearance that forms an "El" to provide a frontage on the Avenue, between 78th and 78th Streets. The apartment house to rise here is the Kensington. The former home of Mrs. Jacob H. Schiff stood here from about 1901. Occupying the corner locations are the 16 story No. 960 Fifth Avenue and the darker 15.story No. 969. The latter is of recent construction, the former dating from 1926 when the mansion of Senator Wm. A. Clark was razed. This structure was of contemporary erection to the Schiff home.

January 20, 1938

Berenice Abbott, photo

Jan. 20, 1938

... showing the Duke home, present proprietor being the wife (Doris Duke) of the U.S. Minister to Canada, James H.R. Cromwell. The latter performed his last official act there on May 17, 1940, to run for the New Jersey seat in the U.S. Senate.
